indicators.justification:
By the LAW OF THE REPUBLIC OF UZBEKISTAN ABOUT PUBLIC PROCUREMENT (ZRU-684, April 22, 2021), the public procurement process involves the following steps:
- public procurement planning;
- implementation of procurement procedures;
- conclusion and execution of the contract;
- monitoring of public procurement.
Procurement procedures can be done electronically.
According to the law, state control in this area is carried out by:
- Accounting Chamber;
- Prosecutor General's Office;
- Anti-Corruption Agency;
- Ministry of Finance;
- Antitrust Committee.
-Citizens, mahallas, non-governmental organizations, and the media also have the right to exercise public control in the field.
The data on public procurement processes is available as open data on the open data portal of the Republic of Uzbekistan[2]. But the data is not complete, detailed, and error-free, not placed regularly and on time. Only the name of some information is provided by some organizations, with part of the information omitted. Some information only lists the names and numbers of goods and services purchased, and does not say when or how much was spent. Historical data  that allows users to track change over time is not available. There is no possibility of comparison in the data. Data searches are not placed on the portal in a way that is easy to find. Data is available only in Uzbek.

Sources: 
